dive.notes:
There were a few dive boats here and divers doing deco. stops on the shot line. Graham Nash came with us to float as Patrick isn't yet a Sports Diver.
The wreck/artificial reef was interesting. I came down the shot line to the bridge. There was a big hold cut in the roof and I went in to get a few shots. The Scylla has been under the water now for 6+ years and there lots of life start to cling all over it. The deepest point I got to was when we drifted over the side at one point, which put us at 18.6m. The hull goes down to 24m although we didn't do this.
I had difficulty with boyancy here. I wasn't able to hold a stop at 8m. I think I was coming up faster then I couldn't dump air fast enough. Just to be safe I didn't go on the second dive of the day.
http://www.divesitedirectory.co.uk/dive_site_uk_england_southwest_wreck_hms_scylla.html

Dicky found a snow crab here hiding amoungst the Kelp and ridges. The tide was starting to come in. The cox noticed there was a peak rising up from 9m to 2m which we all entered the water around. The GPS for it is on the boat computer.

This dive contains three caves in a reef wall. The current was very strong, the strongest I've experienced so far. Had to haul myself down the shot line. There were lots of fish hidding in nooks and crannies in the reef. We saw trumpet fish, red snappers, angel fish, conger eel. DM brought us back to shot line, however not directly after we indicated 100 and then 50 bar. This resulted in Yoke have to buddy breath at 5m. I was down to 20bar. The current got stronger while trying to hold 3min stop at 5min. The shot line snapped and we were whisked to the surface. The DM said these were the worst conditions he'd seen in years. Stressful dive with terrible visibility. I was quite unhappy with DM as we should have started back earlier or came up and not got to the air sharing situation.

Much calmer dive with a smaller current. Dived down the shot line to 20m. The visibility wasn't much better. We swam the reef overhang at the bottom. Lots of fish were hiding in cracks. Got a great shot of a nudibranch with the aid of the DM's LED torch. We ascended to 15m to swim a long the top of reef and back towards the shot line. I was still too low on air getting to the surface then I would have liked.
